Ethereum should now consume [ https://substack.com/redirect/5d6aa12e-c3b8-4=
c5d-9156-f3009d0009d6?r=3D9p0gt ] 99.9% or so less energy. It's like Finlan=
d has suddenly shut off its power grid, according to one estimate [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/793b5962-01d8-48dc-97fa-11ee9748028b?r=3D9p0gt ]. Et=
hereum=E2=80=99s developers say the upgrade will make the network =E2=80=93=
 which houses a $60 billion [ https://substack.com/redirect/35f6e8e2-cc04-4=
623-ab62-864b8aae922e?r=3D9p0gt ] ecosystem of cryptocurrency exchanges, le=
nding companies, non-fungible token (NFT) marketplaces and other apps =E2=
=80=93 more secure and scalable, too.
It happened. WMI. After almost half a decade of delays, the Ethereum Merge =
was completed on Thursday. Without getting too into the nitty-gritty (we we=
nt way, way deep on Ethereum in Own the Internet [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/9e97a9c7-bfe5-465b-baba-1bea0cb4a764?r=3D9p0gt ] for those curious), =
the highly anticipated Merge moves the Ethereum blockchain from a =E2=80=9C=
proof-of-work=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cproof-of-stake=E2=80=9D consensus mechan=
ism. While the merge doesn=E2=80=99t solve all of Ethereum=E2=80=99s issues=
 =E2=80=94 namely, it doesn=E2=80=99t make it faster or cheaper (that=E2=80=
=99s for future planned upgrades) =E2=80=94 it does reduce the blockchain=
=E2=80=99s energy consumption by ~99.9% and lets owners stake their ETH to =
generate a yield in exchange for maintaining the ledger.=20
Perhaps more importantly, though, is the fact that it happened. The Merge w=
as held up for years due to technical complexity, coordination difficulties=
, and politics =E2=80=94 but it finally happened. One of the most consequen=
tial systems upgrades in history went through without a hitch. According to=
 Vitalik, the Merge is just the beginning:=20
"To me, the Merge just symbolizes the difference between early stage Ethere=
um, and the Ethereum we've always wanted ... to become. So let's go build o=
ut all of the other parts of this ecosystem and turn Ethereum into what we =
want it to be."
(4) DOE Report Finds Hundreds of Retiring Coal Plant Sites Could Convert to=
 Nuclear [ https://substack.com/redirect/f8382d1f-7373-463b-ae2e-b8b903ad84=
e0?r=3D9p0gt ]
From the Office of Nuclear Energy
The study investigated the benefits and challenges of converting retiring c=
oal plant sites into nuclear plant sites. After screening recently retired =
and active coal plant sites, the study team identified 157 retired coal pla=
nt sites and 237 operating coal plant sites as potential candidates for a c=
oal-to-nuclear transition. Of these sites, the team found that 80% are good=
 candidates to host advanced reactors smaller than the gigawatt scale.
It=E2=80=99s become increasingly apparent (or at least politically more acc=
eptable) that nuclear energy is going to play a big part in achieving the U=
=2ES.=E2=80=99 emissions goals. As we wro=
te about in =E2=80=9CWorking Harder =
and Smarter [ https://substack.com/redirect/dd21280e-4564-4495-874e-2f5c2ed=
a629e?r=3D9p0gt ],=E2=80=9D if we=E2=80=99re going to realize the full pote=
ntial of the Abundance Renaissance, we are going to need a lot more energy.=
=20
According to the Department of Energy=E2=80=99s report, the coal-to-nuclear=
 transition will not only make our energy grid cleaner, but unlock new buil=
ding opportunities, jobs and tax revenues. But we won=E2=80=99t need to sta=
rt from scratch =E2=80=94 much of our existing infrastructure can repurpose=
d to power this next wave of energy production. The potential benefits are =
staggering. From the report:
Greenhouse gas emissions in a region could fall by 86% when nuclear power p=
lants replace large coal plants, which is equivalent to taking more than 50=
0,000 gasoline-powered passenger vehicles off the roads.
For each conversion, jobs in the region could increase by more than 650 per=
manent positions.=20
Long-term job impacts could lead to additional annual economic activity of =
$275 million, implying an increase of 92% tax revenue for the local county =
when compared to the operating coal power.
The reuse of coal infrastructure for advanced nuclear reactors could also r=
educe costs for developing new nuclear technology, saving from 15% to 35% i=
n construction costs.
IT=E2=80=99S TIME TO CONVERT.
(5) Billionaire No More: Patagonia Founder Gives Away the Company [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/39b5daa1-975c-4498-ab22-fc6fb7fcde1c?r=3D9p0gt ]
David Gelles [ https://substack.com/redirect/827183f0-59c2-40fd-a62e-9d90ef=
2c63f8?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
Rather than selling the company or taking it public, Mr. Chouinard, his wif=
e and two adult children have transferred their ownership of Patagonia, val=
ued at about $3 billion, to a specially designed trust and a nonprofit orga=
nization. They were created to preserve the company=E2=80=99s independence =
and ensure that all of its profits =E2=80=94 some $100 million a year =E2=
=80=94 are used to combat climate change and protect undeveloped land aroun=
d the globe.
In a move that many Patagonia vest-wearing types may not agree with, Yvon C=
houinard, has essentially given away his $3 billion ($100 million per year =
cash flow) apparel brand to a climate-focused non-profit. And, believe it o=
r not, according to The New York Times, he didn=E2=80=99t do it to take adv=
antage of any kind of tax loophole.=20
Chouniard=E2=80=99s motivation seems two-fold:=20
1) Influence a new form of =E2=80=9Ccapitalism x philanthropy=E2=80=9D=20
2) Give away as much of his personal wealth to fighting the impacts of clim=
ate change
On the first motivation, we could lay out all the reasons why this won=E2=
=80=99t work and share lessons on incentives and capitalism =E2=80=94 but f=
uck it, if Chouinard wants to give away his fortune to test out this new mo=
del, more power to him. What=E2=80=99s the worst that could happen? The exp=
eriment fails, Patagonia slowly declines, and we=E2=80=99re all short one l=
uxury outdoor clothing brand?=20
But the upside case for Patagonia here is that there is such brand x missio=
n alignment that any of the negative side effects of missing personal finan=
cial incentives are offset by the customer loyalty they win from making suc=
h a move. Patagonia=E2=80=99s most important customers will likely now spen=
d more at Patagonia over the course of their lifetime. Let=E2=80=99s say th=
at the lack of financial incentive means that Patagonia will be managed 20%=
 worse over the next ten years=E2=80=A6I=E2=80=99d bet, though, that this m=
ove increases CLTV by greater than 20% over that same period. This was a br=
illiant marketing move, intentional or not.
Bonus: Adobe Acquires Figma for $20 Billion [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/fe65041d-6728-41d6-9729-176886484588?r=3D9p0gt ]
Not Boring wouldn=E2=80=99t be Not Boring without Figma. It=E2=80=99s one o=
f my favorite pieces of software because it turned me from someone who neve=
r thought of myself as visually creative into someone who loves making the =
images that spice up this newsletter.=20
Particularly in a market like this, it=E2=80=99s nice to see a monster acqu=
isition =E2=80=94 the largest of a private software company in history =E2=
=80=94 happen. It=E2=80=99s a win for the good people, and will create a ne=
w batch of design-focused angel investors, including CEO Dylan Field [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/7a8e8ba4-ef24-440a-8e70-e842526362c9?r=3D9p0gt ],=
 who can help build the next wave of beautifully designed, magical products=
=2E The internet is about to get more delightful.
Humans are pulling off some pretty incredible things every week. Whenever y=
ou find examples, share them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f5a34a1-=
9a37-429b-a896-a1fbc2f315bb?r=3D9p0gt ] and we=E2=80=99ll feature some in t=
he newsletter.
Have a great weekend and look out for a magical post in your inbox on Monda=
y morning.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

